x4freetext: Experiment performed at Duke storage
ring using Compton backscattering of free-electron
laser photons on stored electrons
3He gas target consisting of
cylindrical bottle filled with 170 bar of 3He gas.
The pressurized gas inside the bottle was 99.87% 3He.
Neutron detector consists of a cell filled
with BC-501A organic scintillating liquid coupled to
a photomultiplier tube. The active volume of each
cell has a diameter of 12.7 cm and a length of 5.1
cm. The seven primary detectors were placed at the
angles of 50., 75., 90. (beam right), 90. (beam
left), 105., 130., and 160. relative to the gamma
ray beam direction.
Two identical detectors were used to monitor the gamma
ray beam using D(g,n)H monitor reaction.
Neutron energy was determined by time of
flight technique. Pulse shape discrimination was
used to reduce background.
Quasi monoenergetic photons were produced by
Compton backscattering of free electron laser photons
from two electron bunches stored in electron storage
ring. Revolution frequency of single bunch was 2.79MHz.
Photon energy spread was 5-6%, beam intensity of
(2-7)E+7 photons/sec on target was reached.
